  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contract obligations to Ohio in FY2026 to date total $4.9B across 41,537 awards with an average award size of $118K. Obligations are down 50.2% year over year. Historical annual obligations show prior-year levels of $8.4B in FY21, $7.8B in FY22, $10.1B in FY23, $9B in FY24, and $9.8B in FY25, with the current fiscal-year-to-date total of $4.9B representing the partial FY2026 period. The Department of Defense accounts for the largest share of buying agency obligations at $3.2B, followed by the General Services Administration at $393M and the Department of Energy at $332M. Top vendors by obligations include GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY at $511M, MARATHON PETROLEUM COMPANY LP at $352M, and SOUTHERN OHIO CLEANUP COMPANY LLC at $243M. Leading industries by obligations are Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences at $771M, Aircraft Engine and Engine Parts Manufacturing at $472M, and Petroleum Refineries at $397M. All figures are contract obligations; current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date).",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How has federal contracting in Ohio trended recently?",
        "body": "Obligations in FY2026 to date total $4.9B, down 50.2% year over year. Annual obligations in recent fiscal years were $8.4B in FY21, $7.8B in FY22, $10.1B in FY23, $9B in FY24, and $9.8B in FY25, showing higher totals in those prior years compared with the partial FY2026 figure. The FY2026 total represents a fiscal year to date snapshot rather than a full-year sum. These amounts are contract obligations."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies and vendors dominate federal spending in Ohio?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense leads with $3.2B in obligations, followed by the General Services Administration at $393M and the Department of Energy at $332M. Top vendors include GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY at $511M, MARATHON PETROLEUM COMPANY LP at $352M, and SOUTHERN OHIO CLEANUP COMPANY LLC at $243M. Key industry concentrations are Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences at $771M and Aircraft Engine and Engine Parts Manufacturing at $472M."
      }
